<Base title="PSALM — Method">
  <section>
    <h2>The idea, plainly</h2>
    <p>
      A child learns language from a few million words, not a few trillion. PSALM
      borrows that spirit. Instead of pouring more text into a small model, we give
      it a short, dense lesson in <em>structure</em> first — generated by Pāṇini's
      grammar of Sanskrit — and only then let it read ordinary English. The
      experiment asks a sharp question: when the total amount of text is held
      fixed, does the kind of structural lesson you start with change how well the
      model ends up understanding language?
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>One model, read three ways</h2>
    <p>
      A single small bidirectional encoder is trained once and evaluated along
      three axes: English structural generalization on the public BabyLM
      benchmarks, Sanskrit linguistic competence on morphology and word-order
      tasks, and the cross-lingual gap between a grammar-primed model and a plain
      baseline. The model does not choose an identity; it is trained on all three
      signals and measured on all three, so the same weights answer the
      competition question and the scientific one.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>The four-arm, token-matched test</h2>
    <p>
      The heart of the study is an ablation in which four conditions share one
      English pretraining corpus and differ only in the structural dose given
      beforehand, with every dose trimmed to the same token budget. The English
      dose is a control that holds budget fixed while contributing no foreign
      structure; the Pāṇinian dose carries grammatical form with gold kāraka
      roles; the Dyck dose carries hierarchy without meaning; and the Paribhāṣā
      dose carries typed Navya-Nyāya semantic graphs. Because the budget is
      identical, any difference at the end belongs to the dose and not to how much
      text was read.
    </p>
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Arm</th><th>Dose</th><th>What it isolates</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>A</td><td>English (control)</td><td>budget held fixed, no foreign structure</td></tr>
        <tr><td>B</td><td>Pāṇinian Sanskrit</td><td>grammatical form + kāraka roles</td></tr>
        <tr><td>C</td><td>k-Shuffle Dyck</td><td>hierarchy without semantics</td></tr>
        <tr><td>D</td><td>Paribhāṣā graphs</td><td>typed semantic structure</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>The Śabdabodha pipeline</h2>
    <p>
      Arm D's dose is produced automatically. Every generated Sanskrit sentence is
      parsed for its kāraka structure by the Vidyut engine, converted by
      Vyutpattivāda rules into a typed semantic graph, and linearized into a string
      the model can read — a deterministic path from sentence to meaning that needs
      no human annotation. This is the project's most distinctive engineering
      contribution: a grammar and a logic, together, manufacturing their own
      supervised data.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>How we measure, and how we stay honest</h2>
    <p>
      Minimal-pair and world-knowledge tasks are scored without task-specific heads
      by reading pseudo-log-likelihoods directly off the masked model, and the
      (Super)GLUE tasks are read with a light classifier fine-tune. Every reported
      contrast carries bootstrap confidence intervals and Holm–Bonferroni
      correction against thresholds fixed before the numbers were computed. A
      separate leaderboard-submission track may add data-efficiency mechanisms such
      as a decaying masking schedule and the Muon optimizer, but those are kept
      strictly out of the ablation so they can never flatter the scientific
      comparison.
    </p>
  </section>
</Base>
